WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.080
[Amit Varma]: Religion is about a lot more than God, and that is more visible in India than anywhere

00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:12.080
[Amit Varma]: else.

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:16.040
[Amit Varma]: I am a non-believer, and if belief in God was all there was to religion, then I could

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:17.280
[Amit Varma]: just ignore it.

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:19.360
[Amit Varma]: But there's much more to it than that.

00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:24.360
[Amit Varma]: Religion can give people a sense of community, often even unity, and shapes, cultures and

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:26.160
[Amit Varma]: cuisines and art.

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:31.200
[Amit Varma]: On the flip side, it can play to our worst tribalistic instincts and divide people, just

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:32.560
[Amit Varma]: as it can unite them.

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:37.040
[Amit Varma]: I often say on the show that people contain multitudes, or India contains multitudes,

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:41.280
[Amit Varma]: and when it comes to religion, this is actually more true of India than perhaps any other

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:42.640
[Amit Varma]: place in the world.

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:47.080
[Amit Varma]: All the religions in the world exist here, even thrive here, and we have more gods and

00:00:47.080 --> 00:00:53.080
[Amit Varma]: goddesses in India than even spices, and indeed, the one area that most reflects this incredible

00:00:53.080 --> 00:00:56.140
[Amit Varma]: melting pot of a nation is our food.

00:00:56.140 --> 00:01:00.760
[Amit Varma]: And whether or not you believe in God, I think we can both agree that Indian food can be

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:07.560
[Amit Varma]: divine, and religion has played a part in that.

00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:12.760
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:13.760
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:19.760
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:21.040
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:24.440
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is a prolific columnist and author, Shobha Narayan.

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:28.960
[Amit Varma]: Shobha has just come out with a fascinating book called Food and Faith, A Pilgrim's Journey

