00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:15.960
[Amit Varma]: Shobha, welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:17.680
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for having me, Amit.

00:03:17.680 --> 00:03:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Shobha, I loved reading your superb book.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:26.040
[Amit Varma]: But before we kind of get to the book, I'm also sort of fascinated by your journey in

00:03:26.040 --> 00:03:29.620
[Amit Varma]: the sense that I've read your column for many years in Mint and so on.

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:33.800
[Amit Varma]: And whenever I read anything by you, I mean, the three things I would typically associate

00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:35.680
[Amit Varma]: you with are food, travel and writing.

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:39.400
[Amit Varma]: And of course, you write a lot about food and travel.

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:43.640
[Amit Varma]: But you've also, you know, done journalism in Colombia and so on.

00:03:43.640 --> 00:03:48.960
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about your background and your sort of journey of, you know, living

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:52.680
[Amit Varma]: in different places in the world and how that affected what you do.

00:03:52.680 --> 00:03:54.120
[Guest]: I grew up in Chennai.

00:03:54.120 --> 00:03:58.560
[Guest]: And I was one of those kids who knew early on that I wanted to be a writer.

00:03:58.560 --> 00:04:02.960
[Guest]: Even while I was in college in Women's Christian College in Chennai, I used to write for the

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:04.560
[Guest]: Indian Express and Aside.

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:10.200
[Guest]: There was this wonderful magazine called Aside in Chennai, which was run by Janaki Venkatraman.

00:04:10.200 --> 00:04:14.360
[Guest]: Those days, there were no emails, so I walked up to her and said, Can I write for you?

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:15.840
[Guest]: And she agreed.

00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:20.840
[Guest]: And I used to write columns occasionally for the Indian Express, which at that time was

00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:23.360
[Guest]: edited by Rajmohan Gandhi.

00:04:23.360 --> 00:04:25.960
[Guest]: So very illustrious man, as you know.

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:29.560
[Guest]: So as a college student, I wrote, as a school student, I wrote poetry.

00:04:29.560 --> 00:04:33.320
[Guest]: So I was one of those kids who just has written all her life.

00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:39.200
[Guest]: I took a detour in college, when I went abroad to complete my undergraduate, I studied art

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:40.880
[Guest]: and sculpture.

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:45.080
[Guest]: And I have since developed an interest in that.

00:04:45.080 --> 00:04:49.660
[Guest]: I went to a women's college there, too, called Mount Holyoke, where I did art.

00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:55.720
[Guest]: And then after a master's in finance, I finally returned to journalism at the Columbia J School.

00:04:55.720 --> 00:04:57.040
[Guest]: It was a one year program.

00:04:57.040 --> 00:04:59.880
[Guest]: It was a boot camp in many words.

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:03.300
[Guest]: You had to ride in the back of a police car to do police reporting.

00:05:03.300 --> 00:05:08.560
[Guest]: You had to go to the criminal courts to write about law and trials and things like that.

00:05:08.560 --> 00:05:12.160
[Guest]: But I have always been drawn to memoirs.

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:18.280
[Guest]: And my first break in food writing came when the New York Times announced a competition.

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:24.120
[Guest]: They took a half page ad and said, write 150 words about food.

00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:29.880
[Guest]: And if your essay is chosen by Ruth Reisel, who was then the restaurant critic of the

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:34.880
[Guest]: New York Times, we will give you a $1,000 coupon to use as you wish.

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:40.640
[Guest]: So as an impoverished student, the appeal of getting $1,000 to dine in New York was

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:43.040
[Guest]: very irresistible.

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:49.560
[Guest]: So I discovered, you know, writing 150 words and making an essay in that, in some ways

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:54.960
[Guest]: harder than writing 850 words, which is what you and I do for our letters and blogs and

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:55.960
[Guest]: columns.

00:05:55.960 --> 00:06:01.120
[Guest]: So condensing a narrative in 150 words was difficult.

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:03.120
[Guest]: I did it and I won the prize.

00:06:03.120 --> 00:06:06.760
[Guest]: I should have dug up the essay, which I could have read to you.

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:11.600
[Guest]: But it was about India, 1986.

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:16.000
[Guest]: I want to study in America, but my grandparents will not allow me.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:21.640
[Guest]: Finally, the elders decide that they will ask me to prepare a feast, one that they are

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:25.000
[Guest]: sure I will fail because I don't know cooking.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:28.400
[Guest]: And so I take up the challenge and then I describe the feast.

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:35.360
[Guest]: And each line had, so there was the bindi roasted in oil with fennel seeds.

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:41.040
[Guest]: And then there was the rasam piping hot with a sprinkling of coriander leaves on top.

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:48.040
[Guest]: There was rice served with streams of mist on top and ghee, golden ghee.

00:06:48.040 --> 00:06:52.440
[Guest]: So essentially it was a practice in food writing, so the practice in describing food in a very

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:53.440
[Guest]: condensed way.

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:59.520
[Guest]: So when I won the award, I got this $1,000 coupon, which I dined away.

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:05.760
[Guest]: And Ruth Reichel, who went on from The Times to edit Gourmet, which is the late great gourmet,

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:11.040
[Guest]: as I call it, she said, why don't you expand this 150 word essay and make it into 1,500

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:12.040
[Guest]: words?

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:14.560
[Guest]: And that was how the food writing began.

00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:18.880
[Guest]: They called it The God of Small Feasts and it was published in Gourmet.

00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:26.400
[Guest]: And beginner's luck, it won this James Beard Award for the MFK Fisher Award for Distinguished

00:07:26.400 --> 00:07:28.320
[Guest]: Food Writing was big.

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:33.800
[Guest]: And that was how I first learned about MFK Fisher and I went on to read her book.

00:07:33.800 --> 00:07:39.760
[Guest]: And then just kept writing about food and wine, Bon Appetit, Gourmet while I was in

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:45.360
[Guest]: Manhattan and then moved to India and wrote about food as well for Mint.

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:50.600
[Amit Varma]: Wow, that's quite a mind blowing story and to do it in 150 words seems to me almost impossible.

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:55.440
[Amit Varma]: Like when I teach my writing course, I often quote Blaise Pascal's famous quote about when

00:07:55.440 --> 00:07:59.320
[Amit Varma]: he wrote a letter to someone and he said, you know, quote, apologies for sending you

00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:00.320
[Amit Varma]: a long letter.

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:06.080
[Amit Varma]: I did not have time to write you a short one, stop quote.

00:08:06.080 --> 00:08:10.960
[Amit Varma]: I think anyone who's ever written to a word count or a deadline knows exactly how hard

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:11.960
[Amit Varma]: it is.

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:14.640
[Amit Varma]: So and while you were describing it to me just now, you know, even though I just had

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:18.480
[Amit Varma]: my brunch, my mouth was kind of watering right away.

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:22.680
[Amit Varma]: So you know, what is it that drew you to food writing in particular?

00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:26.400
[Amit Varma]: Like was it that this challenge came up and you liked food and you liked writing and you

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:29.760
[Amit Varma]: said that, okay, I'll, you know, combine these two and try it out?

00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:32.600
[Amit Varma]: Or were you already reading food writers?

00:08:32.600 --> 00:08:36.840
[Amit Varma]: If so, who were the writers, food writers and otherwise, who you really enjoyed and

00:08:36.840 --> 00:08:41.320
[Amit Varma]: thought that they might, you know, shine a light on the kind of writing that you want

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:42.480
[Amit Varma]: to do?

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:46.760
[Amit Varma]: So what was that process of evolving as a writer and, and then as a food writer, because

00:08:46.760 --> 00:08:50.840
[Amit Varma]: it strikes me that, you know, when one starts writing about food, you will sort of begin

00:08:50.840 --> 00:08:56.120
[Amit Varma]: by writing about the sensory experience of the food, the smells, the taste, the look

00:08:56.120 --> 00:08:57.540
[Amit Varma]: of it, all of that.

00:08:57.540 --> 00:09:02.720
[Amit Varma]: But then you move on as indeed you have in this book, you move on to the wider cultural

00:09:02.720 --> 00:09:07.560
[Amit Varma]: and social significances and the resonances that food carries.

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:12.480
[Amit Varma]: So you know, was that there from the start or is that something that you kind of, that

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:15.480
[Amit Varma]: evolved within your writing as well?

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:16.480
[Guest]: Thank you.

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:19.080
[Guest]: So Amit, as you know, there are two types of food writing.

00:09:19.080 --> 00:09:24.200
[Guest]: One is the writing of recipes and cookbooks and the other is the kind of work that I do.

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:27.040
[Guest]: I'm not a good cook in my kitchen.

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:32.440
[Guest]: And I stumbled on food writing, unlike writing in general, where I was one of those kids

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:33.440
[Guest]: who wrote.

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:35.640
[Guest]: Food writing didn't come naturally to me.

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:41.360
[Guest]: While in Chennai, I wrote about sabas and music and, you know, whatever the editor assigned

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:42.360
[Guest]: me to do.

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:48.240
[Guest]: Food writing literally was a break, a fortunate happenstance, a discovery of a skill that

00:09:48.240 --> 00:09:52.880
[Guest]: I didn't know existed because all in pursuit of $1,000 of a food coupon.

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:54.760
[Guest]: And since then, I have worked at it.

00:09:54.760 --> 00:09:58.360
[Guest]: I think food writing is different from cooking.

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:01.260
[Guest]: I don't think the two are together.

00:10:01.260 --> 00:10:04.720
[Guest]: In order to write about food, you don't need to be a good cook.

00:10:04.720 --> 00:10:06.720
[Guest]: You need to have a good palate.

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:07.720
[Guest]: And as M.S.K.

00:10:07.720 --> 00:10:12.000
[Guest]: Fisher said, you need to have the capacity to eat prodigious amounts of food.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.240
[Guest]: And as you are eating it, to think about it, you need to have taste and you need to have

00:10:16.240 --> 00:10:17.240
[Guest]: good eye to observe.

00:10:17.240 --> 00:10:24.680
[Guest]: So Meenakshi Amal's classic book, Samaythi Paar, which every Tamilian has and carries

00:10:24.680 --> 00:10:27.480
[Guest]: this three volumes, is a precision.

00:10:27.480 --> 00:10:32.600
[Guest]: It is about use of this particular type of rice cooked to this particular amount.

00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:37.920
[Guest]: And she even describes how you, the Tamil word is aathardhu, which means to make cool.

00:10:37.920 --> 00:10:40.680
[Guest]: There are ways in which you make cool before.

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:44.920
[Guest]: For example, in Tamil cooking, there is a dish called beans paruppuursali, which is

00:10:44.920 --> 00:10:49.320
[Guest]: beans in which you put the channaikkadal and you grind it and then you put it in.

00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:51.320
[Guest]: And then you steam it.

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:53.680
[Guest]: And then she describes how you cool it.

00:10:53.680 --> 00:10:57.840
[Guest]: You put, I mean, in the olden days, my grandmother would put it out on a rice cloth, an old stone

00:10:57.840 --> 00:10:59.920
[Guest]: dhoti and cool it.

00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:06.080
[Guest]: So that is a very precise type of Kubuk kind of observation, how you cool, how you cook,

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:11.120
[Guest]: how long you cook and what is the smell that emanates when the idli is done.

00:11:11.120 --> 00:11:20.080
[Guest]: The kind of writing I do involves being, to quote Isaiah Berlin, the fox and the hedgehog,

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:24.960
[Guest]: you need to have a wide spectrum, the surface area has to be quite large and you need to

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:32.840
[Guest]: be able to connect history and philosophy and feminism for me and sensuality and India.

00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:34.960
[Guest]: So that's what my kind of writing does.

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:41.200
[Guest]: And how did I cultivate that skill is I think that reading a lot, as you say, I was introduced

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:49.480
[Guest]: after writing to all the big American writers and Katie Achaya is a must read if you are

00:11:49.480 --> 00:11:50.840
[Guest]: an Indian food writer.

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:57.600
[Guest]: I read Bikram Doctor's columns religiously, I read Harold McGee who wrote an encyclopedia

00:11:57.600 --> 00:11:58.880
[Guest]: about food.

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:00.920
[Guest]: And then, I mean, I have a long list.

00:12:00.920 --> 00:12:05.000
[Guest]: While in gourmet, one of the pleasures was to be exposed to food writers.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:10.720
[Guest]: So Fuchsia Dunlap's books on Chinese cooking is one that I read.

00:12:10.720 --> 00:12:14.360
[Guest]: Michael Pollan, of course, although now he's overused, everybody reads him.

00:12:14.360 --> 00:12:21.680
[Guest]: There's a wonderful book called The Man Who Ate Everything, written by Jeffrey Steingarten.

00:12:21.680 --> 00:12:23.980
[Guest]: He was the food columnist for Vogue.

00:12:23.980 --> 00:12:27.880
[Guest]: And he wrote this fantastic book of essays called The Man Who Ate Everything.

00:12:27.880 --> 00:12:32.680
[Guest]: And then in it, for example, he will take French fries, and he will conduct experiment

00:12:32.680 --> 00:12:36.000
[Guest]: to see which is the best kind of French fry and how you make it.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:37.240
[Guest]: So those are that.

00:12:37.240 --> 00:12:44.640
[Guest]: I loved a book called Feast, the Food of the Islamic World by a woman called Anisa Helou.

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:50.360
[Guest]: And if I'm pronouncing it right, and what was fantastic about that is as a vegetarian,

00:12:50.360 --> 00:12:56.160
[Guest]: you tend to basically keep away, I mean, you think that books that focus on non-vegetarian

00:12:56.160 --> 00:12:57.840
[Guest]: food are not useful to you.

00:12:57.840 --> 00:13:02.480
[Guest]: But this book, for example, even though I don't eat meat kebab, she places them side

00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:07.840
[Guest]: by side by side and then describes how a Turkish kebab is different from a Iranian kebab, from

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:10.880
[Guest]: an Iraqi, Iraq kebab in Iraq.

00:13:10.880 --> 00:13:16.880
[Guest]: And it was an experience of description of the kind that is very useful to me and of

00:13:16.880 --> 00:13:23.040
[Guest]: history and milieu and stories and community and family and cooking.

00:13:23.040 --> 00:13:24.920
[Guest]: Cooking comes last in a way.

00:13:24.920 --> 00:13:26.360
[Guest]: So that was good.

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:31.360
[Guest]: Then once you get into it, again, Vikram's columns will introduce me to Manasol Lhasa.

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:37.520
[Guest]: These are Sanskrit texts from the old, K.P. Acharya talks about it a lot.

00:13:37.520 --> 00:13:39.560
[Guest]: So these are the things I read.

00:13:39.560 --> 00:13:44.760
[Guest]: And then there's an Indian book by Colleen Taylor Senner called Feasts and Fasts.

00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:51.440
[Guest]: That's a wonderful book because it anchors food history in India in a very scholarly

00:13:51.440 --> 00:13:52.440
[Guest]: way.

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:58.560
[Guest]: So for example, there are recipes for barbecued rat and there are recipes that basically convince

00:13:58.560 --> 00:14:04.800
[Guest]: you that we were not the prudes that we have become in terms of our attitude towards animals,

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:11.640
[Guest]: certainly the cow and our attitudes towards meat and our attitudes towards cooking and

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:17.520
[Guest]: this whole purity and non-purity that has invaded the Brahminical kitchen since.

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:18.960
[Guest]: So that was good.

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:24.560
[Guest]: So then I can give you a longer list if you like, but that's a start.

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:28.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and you've actually, you know, with this answer, you actually you said you can't

00:14:28.560 --> 00:14:32.560
[Amit Varma]: cook, but you've provided a feast of reading for my listeners and for me, because I'm sure

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:35.480
[Amit Varma]: many of these books are now going to get gobbled up by us.

00:14:35.480 --> 00:14:37.760
[Amit Varma]: And of course, we share our admiration of Vikram Docter.

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:38.760
[Amit Varma]: He's a good friend.

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:42.440
[Amit Varma]: He's been on the show, in fact, talking about the Indianness of Indian food was the name

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:43.440
[Amit Varma]: of the episode.

00:14:43.440 --> 00:14:47.720
[Amit Varma]: And it was all about almost how everything that we consider Indian is from somewhere

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:48.720
[Amit Varma]: else.

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:53.680
[Amit Varma]: So I kind of have a question also about how writing about something can shape a person

00:14:53.680 --> 00:14:57.720
[Amit Varma]: like at the obvious level, like this is again a sort of a two part question.

00:14:57.720 --> 00:15:00.520
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it's really the same question, but two different directions.

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:05.080
[Amit Varma]: And one is obviously that one would expect that when you begin writing about food, obviously

00:15:05.080 --> 00:15:10.240
[Amit Varma]: your palate will get more refined because you will pay more attention and be more mindful

00:15:10.240 --> 00:15:14.800
[Amit Varma]: about all the individual things that go into what you're eating and the processes and so

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:15.800
[Amit Varma]: on.

00:15:15.800 --> 00:15:16.800
[Amit Varma]: So did that happen with you?

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:21.840
[Amit Varma]: And the second part is the kind of food writing that you have done would also then mean that

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:26.040
[Amit Varma]: you're not only expanding your palate, but you're also expanding your mind because you

00:15:26.040 --> 00:15:31.280
[Amit Varma]: want to make these cultural connections, these social connections, historical connections,

00:15:31.280 --> 00:15:32.280
[Amit Varma]: all of that.

00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:38.920
[Amit Varma]: I would imagine that it then, you know, incentivizes you to read much more widely and almost in

00:15:38.920 --> 00:15:42.800
[Amit Varma]: that sense and become a different person than who you would have been if you weren't a food

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:43.800
[Amit Varma]: writer.

00:15:43.800 --> 00:15:44.800
[Amit Varma]: Is there something to that?

00:15:44.800 --> 00:15:48.280
[Guest]: The short answer, Amit, is that yes, it changed my palate.

00:15:48.280 --> 00:15:52.520
[Guest]: It changed my palate in a very specific way, it forced me to pay attention to what I was

00:15:52.520 --> 00:15:53.520
[Guest]: eating.

00:15:53.520 --> 00:15:54.520
[Guest]: You're just gobbling it up.

00:15:54.520 --> 00:16:01.480
[Guest]: So it also defined in sharp focus that I was losing a whole spectrum of taste because I

00:16:01.480 --> 00:16:07.320
[Guest]: happened to be a vegetarian and I have not been able to eat meat or fish or chicken.

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:09.360
[Guest]: A friend of mine said this best.

00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:14.800
[Guest]: He said, eat meat if you want to, just before you die, because then the amount of time that

00:16:14.800 --> 00:16:16.880
[Guest]: you'll spend regretting will be the least.

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:20.760
[Guest]: So that said, I realized that a spectrum is lost to me.

00:16:20.760 --> 00:16:25.080
[Guest]: But what I think what being vegetarian does is that it forces you to pay attention to

00:16:25.080 --> 00:16:28.240
[Guest]: all the other flavors because you're losing out on something.

00:16:28.240 --> 00:16:30.600
[Guest]: So how do you eat is the question.

00:16:30.600 --> 00:16:32.840
[Guest]: How do you eat if you want to write about food?

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:34.400
[Guest]: And how do you take notes?

00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:36.120
[Guest]: How do you keep mental notes?

00:16:36.120 --> 00:16:41.540
[Guest]: Very slowly, start by eating very slowly, start by savoring the food.

00:16:41.540 --> 00:16:46.840
[Guest]: And I think that restaurant menus, for example, I always read them because they give me a

00:16:46.840 --> 00:16:53.280
[Guest]: way of, in India less so, but certainly in other countries, you can tell the chef's influence

00:16:53.280 --> 00:16:55.920
[Guest]: on the menu in the way they have written it.

00:16:55.920 --> 00:17:00.520
[Guest]: So for example, braised, does he use the word boiled or braised potatoes?

00:17:00.520 --> 00:17:05.160
[Guest]: Does he use the word sautéed, beans, or does he use stir fried?

00:17:05.160 --> 00:17:10.800
[Guest]: What is the taste difference between, I mean, just like computer technology has very specific

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:13.480
[Guest]: words, cooking has specific words.

00:17:13.480 --> 00:17:17.800
[Guest]: And the question I always face is that, is it reflected in the taste of the food?

00:17:17.800 --> 00:17:23.360
[Guest]: Chinese food, for example, is entirely about braised, sautéed, vegetables, cabbage, but

00:17:23.360 --> 00:17:27.800
[Guest]: take the fourth cabbage and do it four different ways and see how it tastes differently.

00:17:27.800 --> 00:17:33.200
[Guest]: The other thing I always pay attention to is the environment and restaurants are a great

00:17:33.200 --> 00:17:34.200
[Guest]: place for that.

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:41.800
[Guest]: For example, in India, there is a notion that the chef or the cook's temperament matters,

00:17:41.800 --> 00:17:46.680
[Guest]: which is why if you go to Hare Krishna kitchens, or if you go to temple kitchens, they will

00:17:46.680 --> 00:17:52.160
[Guest]: chant the Lord's name, for example, or there will be peaceful music playing in the background.

00:17:52.160 --> 00:17:57.720
[Guest]: Some of my grandparents' friends, they would not eat outside food because they said that,

00:17:57.720 --> 00:18:03.160
[Guest]: in Tamil, we call it Yenna Padilgal, Yenna Padilgal means the thought stamp of the chef

00:18:03.160 --> 00:18:08.160
[Guest]: matters and it will influence how you eat and it will influence your body.

00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:12.720
[Guest]: I have interviewed chefs in New York, you go into restaurant kitchens of Daniel Boulud

00:18:12.720 --> 00:18:17.600
[Guest]: or John George, or it is a hellhole.

00:18:17.600 --> 00:18:22.320
[Guest]: People are screaming, people are cursing, the food that comes out is sublime.

00:18:22.320 --> 00:18:26.120
[Guest]: So that's the other thing is that the milieu matters.

00:18:26.120 --> 00:18:32.040
[Guest]: How does the chef's temperament get translated to the waiter who describes the food to us?

00:18:32.040 --> 00:18:36.880
[Guest]: There's that whole chain and I pay attention to that and how does it, and the way what

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:42.200
[Guest]: people choose, I studied psychology in Women's Cuisine College as an undergraduate, there

00:18:42.200 --> 00:18:46.680
[Guest]: was this very cool study where people would look at the menu and the first person, if

00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:50.960
[Guest]: they call out what you want, you will sort of be forced to call out something else, even

00:18:50.960 --> 00:18:54.080
[Guest]: if you actually wanted that dish to be different.

00:18:54.080 --> 00:18:58.800
[Guest]: So the psychology of ordering of food in restaurants or the psychology of eating is what I pay

00:18:58.800 --> 00:18:59.800
[Guest]: attention to.

00:18:59.800 --> 00:19:04.160
[Guest]: History is a very obvious one, but that doesn't come in the act of eating.

00:19:04.160 --> 00:19:09.320
[Guest]: When the act of eating, it is about using the fork or the spoon, using the hand, the

00:19:09.320 --> 00:19:14.400
[Guest]: tactility of the fingers, which is how we eat, the culture that invented chopsticks

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:17.920
[Guest]: and why did China invent chopsticks as opposed to the spoon?

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:22.360
[Guest]: So those are the kinds of questions you ponder while you are at the table.

00:19:22.360 --> 00:19:26.800
[Guest]: And I love eating at restaurants and because of all these things.

00:19:26.800 --> 00:19:28.240
[Guest]: The history comes afterwards.

00:19:28.240 --> 00:19:34.080
[Guest]: The history is not linked to a dish in my view, the history is linked to a cuisine.

00:19:34.080 --> 00:19:40.200
[Guest]: So the Middle East is fascinating to me because I think some of the best writers of Middle

00:19:40.200 --> 00:19:44.600
[Guest]: Eastern cuisine are women, but it's such a male-centric culture.

00:19:44.600 --> 00:19:46.240
[Guest]: So how did that happen?

00:19:46.240 --> 00:19:50.960
[Guest]: And then learning about, for example, there was a wonderful cookbook called the Syriana

00:19:50.960 --> 00:19:55.200
[Guest]: Cookbook and by Latika George, I believe it was.

00:19:55.200 --> 00:19:58.600
[Guest]: And the Syrian Christian food is heavily fish-centric.

00:19:58.600 --> 00:20:03.640
[Guest]: I don't eat fish, but what you got out of that cookbook was the milieu of Syrian Christians

00:20:03.640 --> 00:20:08.800
[Guest]: and as somebody who spent a lot of time in Kerala, it was a wonderful read for that reason.

00:20:08.800 --> 00:20:16.840
[Guest]: So to answer your question about palate cultivation, I think slowing down and paying attention,

00:20:16.840 --> 00:20:22.040
[Guest]: making connections as disparate as you can would be the three things I do in terms of

00:20:22.040 --> 00:20:29.960
[Guest]: how it has expanded me is that the slowing down, paying attention, savoring, making disparate

00:20:29.960 --> 00:20:35.520
[Guest]: connections force you to each of those has like a four-factor output, which forces you

00:20:35.520 --> 00:20:40.960
[Guest]: to read four different types of books or come back and research for different types of things.

00:20:40.960 --> 00:20:42.960
[Amit Varma]: So that's what it is.

00:20:42.960 --> 00:20:43.960
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating.

00:20:43.960 --> 00:20:48.880
[Amit Varma]: My other sort of observation about a lot of your writing is that in one sense, even when

00:20:48.880 --> 00:20:53.240
[Amit Varma]: you're writing about food, it is like in this book, I got this sense and more senses and

00:20:53.240 --> 00:20:57.680
[Amit Varma]: the fact that you just went to all these different sites, but that it's a travel book and it's

00:20:57.680 --> 00:21:01.280
[Amit Varma]: not just a travel book in the sense that it is about travel.

00:21:01.280 --> 00:21:05.760
[Amit Varma]: It is your travel book in the sense that it is about your journey, not just your sort

00:21:05.760 --> 00:21:10.760
[Amit Varma]: of physical journey through space, but also how you are evolving and changing.

00:21:10.760 --> 00:21:15.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, before I kind of get to the book, what I was wondering about was that you've lived

00:21:15.040 --> 00:21:17.820
[Amit Varma]: in different countries at different parts of your life.

00:21:17.820 --> 00:21:22.840
[Amit Varma]: You have also written extensively about, you know, first settling into America, then, you

00:21:22.840 --> 00:21:26.120
[Amit Varma]: know, coming back to India and settling in here.

00:21:26.120 --> 00:21:31.240
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that someone who travels like that, who is sort of, in a sense, I wouldn't

00:21:31.240 --> 00:21:35.360
[Amit Varma]: say uprooted because these are all choices that you made, but someone who chooses to

00:21:35.360 --> 00:21:39.720
[Amit Varma]: live somewhere else and then come back somewhere else is forced to do something that others

00:21:39.720 --> 00:21:44.880
[Amit Varma]: who stay in one place are not, which is to constantly re-examine themselves, re-examine

00:21:44.880 --> 00:21:49.760
[Amit Varma]: their sense of self, their self of identity, and all of that, which in the context of religion,

00:21:49.760 --> 00:21:53.320
[Amit Varma]: obviously, there's a lot of in this book, which I'll ask you later.

00:21:53.320 --> 00:21:58.700
[Amit Varma]: But in a general sense, you know, what has that kind of exploration been like?

00:21:58.700 --> 00:22:02.640
[Amit Varma]: Because it always strikes me that, you know, we always assume that individuals are what

00:22:02.640 --> 00:22:04.600
[Amit Varma]: individuals are, right?

00:22:04.600 --> 00:22:08.600
[Amit Varma]: As if it's, you know, you are a fixed person at a given point in time.

00:22:08.600 --> 00:22:12.240
[Amit Varma]: But the point is that, you know, if you had a different set of experiences, you would

00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:15.180
[Amit Varma]: be a fundamentally different person.

00:22:15.180 --> 00:22:17.080
[Amit Varma]: How do you think all of this shaped you?

00:22:17.080 --> 00:22:20.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, was it easy to settle into another culture?

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:24.960
[Amit Varma]: How did it make you look at your own identity as an immigrant and as someone born a Hindu?

00:22:24.960 --> 00:22:26.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, did it make you more open?

00:22:26.560 --> 00:22:31.280
[Amit Varma]: Did it, you know, like some immigrants to the US, for example, become more assertive

00:22:31.280 --> 00:22:33.360
[Amit Varma]: about their cultural roots and all of that?

00:22:33.360 --> 00:22:37.280
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about how that journey happened for you.

00:22:37.280 --> 00:22:42.360
[Guest]: So the gift of being an immigrant is that you straddle two cultures or three cultures

00:22:42.360 --> 00:22:43.920
[Guest]: all the time.

00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:48.680
[Guest]: And it forces you to compare which is a gift for a writer, because really writing is about

00:22:48.680 --> 00:22:53.440
[Guest]: the best way to illustrate what you want to say to your reader, as you just did with Blaise

00:22:53.440 --> 00:22:56.840
[Guest]: Pascal, is to compare or show the other.

00:22:56.840 --> 00:23:02.920
[Guest]: The cost of being an immigrant is that you are always a Trishanku, you don't have roots.

00:23:02.920 --> 00:23:05.440
[Guest]: So that is broadly been my life.

00:23:05.440 --> 00:23:13.000
[Guest]: And I think it's helpful for me, because I grew up, till I moved to America at age 20,

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:14.800
[Guest]: I was a Chennai girl.

00:23:14.800 --> 00:23:19.800
[Guest]: And as I know, from your previous podcast, but the Krisha show, for example, Chennai

00:23:19.800 --> 00:23:24.600
[Guest]: is a very rooted city, it is conservative, it used to be when I was growing up, but that

00:23:24.600 --> 00:23:29.400
[Guest]: was a gift, because it forced it gave you a certain set of parameters that were unchanging

00:23:29.400 --> 00:23:32.280
[Guest]: and that you thought was true for the rest of the world.

00:23:32.280 --> 00:23:38.320
[Guest]: So you go from that to America, where I lived for the next 18 years, or 18 years, Chennai,

00:23:38.320 --> 00:23:41.120
[Guest]: 18 years America, where I was moving all around.

00:23:41.120 --> 00:23:48.680
[Guest]: So I sometimes wonder, Amit, I went as a fresh off the board person and landed in Massachusetts

00:23:48.680 --> 00:23:51.480
[Guest]: in a very liberal college.

00:23:51.480 --> 00:23:55.000
[Guest]: And as a result, I became a Democrat by philosophy.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:24:02.760
[Guest]: And I was just thinking, had I landed in Memphis or Georgia, would my philosophy and politics

00:24:02.760 --> 00:24:03.960
[Guest]: have become Republican?

00:24:03.960 --> 00:24:05.480
[Guest]: I have no answer to that.

00:24:05.480 --> 00:24:10.360
[Guest]: But I think those are the kinds of questions that I asked is that, am I a democratic?

00:24:10.360 --> 00:24:11.360
[Guest]: Am I liberal?

00:24:11.360 --> 00:24:13.360
[Guest]: Because of where I landed.

00:24:13.360 --> 00:24:19.840
[Guest]: And I think what happens when you are hungry to leave your hometown as I was, Chennai,

00:24:19.840 --> 00:24:24.840
[Guest]: it was stifling to me, because I grew up in a fairly large family where everybody had

00:24:24.840 --> 00:24:28.920
[Guest]: an opinion about how much oil I should put in my hair and how long the hair should be,

00:24:28.920 --> 00:24:34.240
[Guest]: what I should eat, how I should dress, so I was ready to just flee.

00:24:34.240 --> 00:24:44.200
[Guest]: And when you go and land as a tabula rasa, which I was, and so open, the influences,

00:24:44.200 --> 00:24:49.320
[Guest]: you're like a child, you're like an infant, and the influences, they shape you and as

00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:51.240
[Guest]: they shaped me.

00:24:51.240 --> 00:25:01.360
[Guest]: I think my deep-rooted, sort of reflexive, taking up for the underdog, whoever the underdog

00:25:01.360 --> 00:25:07.200
[Guest]: is of the moment, comes from my time in Massachusetts, which is very liberal and democratic and has

00:25:07.200 --> 00:25:10.360
[Guest]: a strong social conscience.

00:25:10.360 --> 00:25:17.640
[Guest]: My liberal politics, feminism, Mount Holyoke is one of the Seven Sisters.

00:25:17.640 --> 00:25:23.760
[Guest]: So I went from a mother who said a woman is like a creeper, and you have to sort of creep

00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:30.040
[Guest]: and bind yourself to your new family, to this place where feminism was argued, and I am

00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:31.040
[Guest]: a feminist.

00:25:31.040 --> 00:25:38.600
[Guest]: So I think for anyone who leaves home, whether within a country, like a lot of my friends

00:25:38.600 --> 00:25:45.360
[Guest]: in Bangalore have come from the north or a different country, it forces you to take your

00:25:45.360 --> 00:25:50.200
[Guest]: parents and your family and your community off that pedestal and see them for the people

00:25:50.200 --> 00:25:55.120
[Guest]: with clay feet, people you love, but people with clay feet that they are, and it forces

00:25:55.120 --> 00:26:01.520
[Guest]: you to question everything, and I think that is the point of going away from home.

00:26:01.520 --> 00:26:06.080
[Guest]: And some of us take advantage of it, as I did, and some of us don't, and I think we

00:26:06.080 --> 00:26:07.080
[Guest]: fear it.

00:26:07.080 --> 00:26:08.080
[Guest]: We fear the change.

00:26:08.080 --> 00:26:14.000
[Guest]: So a lot of Indians who went to America in the 60s and 70s became more Indian and became

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:19.120
[Guest]: more encapsulated within their culture, and I wasn't like that.

00:26:19.120 --> 00:26:22.840
[Guest]: I didn't see the point of living abroad if you were not.

00:26:22.840 --> 00:26:29.040
[Guest]: And being an artist helped, so my friends were gay people.

00:26:29.040 --> 00:26:35.680
[Guest]: My closest friend was a lesbian who colored her hair purple, so okay, so if you don't

00:26:35.680 --> 00:26:41.720
[Guest]: take the art, then it's no matter, but I think once you have a family, then there's a tendency

00:26:41.720 --> 00:26:47.280
[Guest]: to go inward and kind of freeze yourself when you left India.

00:26:47.280 --> 00:26:49.000
[Guest]: That's what happens to a lot of Americans.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:52.960
[Guest]: After that, I moved to Singapore, which is a different sort of experience.

00:26:52.960 --> 00:26:55.200
[Guest]: Singapore was a bubble.

00:26:55.200 --> 00:27:01.440
[Guest]: It had the gift of three fantastic cooking cultures, which was the Arab cooking, the

00:27:01.440 --> 00:27:04.120
[Guest]: Chinese cooking, and the Indian cooking.

00:27:04.120 --> 00:27:09.680
[Guest]: So it had that, but other than that, living in Singapore as an immigrant was a bubble

00:27:09.680 --> 00:27:15.440
[Guest]: life, and then I had a choice of moving to Chennai or Bangalore, but my husband could

00:27:15.440 --> 00:27:20.440
[Guest]: not stand Chennai summers or the heat, so we ended up in Bangalore, which is a very

00:27:20.440 --> 00:27:28.000
[Guest]: gentle, welcoming city, which is a city of immigrants, so I'm happy that I landed here.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:34.160
[Guest]: So I think that being an immigrant forces you to examine and question constantly, which

00:27:34.160 --> 00:27:41.240
[Guest]: is a state of dissatisfaction, really, most of your time, and for a person to live with

00:27:41.240 --> 00:27:45.520
[Guest]: that angst is not a happy thing, but it helps with the writing.

00:27:45.520 --> 00:27:50.800
[Amit Varma]: I'll take a detour here and point out something that I loved about your book, which is that

00:27:50.800 --> 00:27:54.880
[Amit Varma]: it's full of so many light touches, it's got a conversational tone, and I was just reminded

00:27:54.880 --> 00:27:58.700
[Amit Varma]: of that when you mentioned having gay friends and a lesbian friend, and there's a delightful

00:27:58.700 --> 00:28:05.600
[Amit Varma]: anecdote in your book about how your lesbian friend was once accosted by another girl who

00:28:05.600 --> 00:28:09.000
[Amit Varma]: wanted to convert her to Christianity and said, why don't you come out and talk with

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:12.280
[Amit Varma]: me for a couple of minutes, and your friend told that girl that I'll come out with you,

00:28:12.280 --> 00:28:16.280
[Amit Varma]: but here's the thing, you know, either you'll save my soul or I'll seduce you.

00:28:16.280 --> 00:28:22.640
[Amit Varma]: So I found that so kind of delightful, and your book is full of these light, charming

00:28:22.640 --> 00:28:26.880
[Amit Varma]: moments that, you know, make a person LOL, so despite, you know, if any of my listeners

00:28:26.880 --> 00:28:31.040
[Amit Varma]: are not interested in either food or faith, you can still have fun.

00:28:31.040 --> 00:28:34.720
[Amit Varma]: So that's sort of your third F there for you.

00:28:34.720 --> 00:28:38.480
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of now go closer to the book, like, you know, you've described this book as a

00:28:38.480 --> 00:28:42.080
[Amit Varma]: book about Hinduism written by a skeptical Hindu.

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:45.960
[Amit Varma]: Now before we talk about the book and about Hinduism, I want to talk about the skeptical

00:28:45.960 --> 00:28:50.240
[Amit Varma]: Hindu, you know, in your afterward, you write about how quote, religion is an inheritance

00:28:50.240 --> 00:28:52.520
[Amit Varma]: and a choice, stop quote.

00:28:52.520 --> 00:28:56.920
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting how it shifts from one to the other for you, like you've written

00:28:56.920 --> 00:29:02.600
[Amit Varma]: about how as a teenager, you were an atheist, then agnostic in your 20s and 30s.

00:29:02.600 --> 00:29:07.120
[Amit Varma]: And you turn to religion again, you know, later in life, so much so that in the introduction

00:29:07.120 --> 00:29:11.840
[Amit Varma]: of this book, you wrote, quote, it defines who I am, perhaps not as much as feminism,

00:29:11.840 --> 00:29:15.600
[Amit Varma]: and certainly not as much as being a writer or a mother, stop quote.

00:29:15.600 --> 00:29:17.200
[Amit Varma]: And this turns to unpack here.

00:29:17.200 --> 00:29:21.560
[Amit Varma]: But I'll just ask you about religion and per se that, you know, what has been the role

00:29:21.560 --> 00:29:23.520
[Amit Varma]: of religion in your life?

00:29:23.520 --> 00:29:27.480
[Amit Varma]: And what's kind of, you know, just as you've made a physical homecoming by, you know, settling

00:29:27.480 --> 00:29:32.360
[Amit Varma]: in India, it seems that your journey with regards to religion is also, you know, gradually

00:29:32.360 --> 00:29:34.280
[Amit Varma]: come that kind of circle do not fully.

00:29:34.280 --> 00:29:38.040
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about the role religion has played in your life and the different

00:29:38.040 --> 00:29:40.600
[Amit Varma]: ways in which you think about it.

00:29:40.600 --> 00:29:46.320
[Guest]: So my mother is what is called a Sri Vidya Upasaka, by which I mean she was, it's a feminine

00:29:46.320 --> 00:29:47.320
[Guest]: goddess cult.

00:29:47.320 --> 00:29:54.640
[Guest]: So I grew up with this, Amit, I grew up in a home, which was, she became this after my

00:29:54.640 --> 00:30:00.080
[Guest]: brother and I left home, she said she caught hold of religion when her children left home.

00:30:00.080 --> 00:30:05.800
[Guest]: Actually, that is a trajectory that many people will follow, because most people take to religion

00:30:05.800 --> 00:30:07.200
[Guest]: when they get older.

00:30:07.200 --> 00:30:08.840
[Guest]: I am similar in that.

00:30:08.840 --> 00:30:11.960
[Guest]: So I'm not and the bell-shaped curve, I'm sort of in the middle.

00:30:11.960 --> 00:30:17.320
[Guest]: In terms of the usefulness of religion, a long time ago, maybe two decades ago, there

00:30:17.320 --> 00:30:23.240
[Guest]: was a cover story in Time magazine about religion and it made this case about how people who

00:30:23.240 --> 00:30:28.080
[Guest]: had faith and it was largely Christian faith, because Time magazine was for the Western

00:30:28.080 --> 00:30:29.080
[Guest]: world.

00:30:29.080 --> 00:30:34.760
[Guest]: And there was a whole slew of benefits that were listed out, you will have better marriages,

00:30:34.760 --> 00:30:39.720
[Guest]: you will have better health, you will have better relationships within the community,

00:30:39.720 --> 00:30:41.720
[Guest]: your immunity will be higher.

00:30:41.720 --> 00:30:46.040
[Guest]: And again, these are narratives that keep coming up now, they say, if you keep a gratitude

00:30:46.040 --> 00:30:49.560
[Guest]: journal, you will have this, this and this and this.

00:30:49.560 --> 00:30:54.640
[Guest]: But I remember I was not part of the self-help genre, I was not paying attention to that.

00:30:54.640 --> 00:30:59.400
[Guest]: So this really sort of caught me out of the blue and said, my God, if Time magazine says

00:30:59.400 --> 00:31:02.200
[Guest]: religion is so great, I better start looking at it.

00:31:02.200 --> 00:31:05.640
[Guest]: And I shelved it away and I just didn't pay attention.

00:31:05.640 --> 00:31:07.120
[Guest]: But so you have two strands.

00:31:07.120 --> 00:31:11.560
[Guest]: One is because perhaps because my mother was so deeply spiritual, I sort of rebelled against

00:31:11.560 --> 00:31:12.760
[Guest]: it.

00:31:12.760 --> 00:31:15.920
[Guest]: And then intellectually seeing the benefit of faith.

00:31:15.920 --> 00:31:20.840
[Guest]: But then faith, as I have come to learn, is a self-experience.

00:31:20.840 --> 00:31:24.760
[Guest]: It's not a cerebral experience, it is a visceral experience.

00:31:24.760 --> 00:31:26.400
[Guest]: And I don't, I'm not there yet.

00:31:26.400 --> 00:31:31.600
[Guest]: I think it would be wonderful to have that visceral experience where monks in the Kumbh

00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:37.560
[Guest]: Mela have experienced transcendence, when they see the Ganga, they just, I mean, and

00:31:37.560 --> 00:31:45.320
[Guest]: here we are saying, you know, in California, drugs have become legal.

00:31:45.320 --> 00:31:47.400
[Guest]: Imagine if you can achieve that without drugs.

00:31:47.400 --> 00:31:49.760
[Guest]: So that's what religion did for you.

00:31:49.760 --> 00:31:53.280
[Guest]: And I've seen it time and time again in India.

00:31:53.280 --> 00:31:59.280
[Guest]: Now, okay, so let's say I've come to a point where I admit faith as a, as an idea into

00:31:59.280 --> 00:32:00.280
[Guest]: my life.

00:32:00.280 --> 00:32:01.280
[Guest]: Which faith?

00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:07.760
[Guest]: Buddhism and Hinduism are both seductive to me, monotheistic faiths don't attract me as

00:32:07.760 --> 00:32:08.760
[Guest]: much.

00:32:08.760 --> 00:32:13.920
[Guest]: Hinduism is a marvelous faith because of, it is a faith that still has not given up

00:32:13.920 --> 00:32:20.280
[Guest]: its very ancient animistic roots, where rocks are worshipped, where trees, we have sacred,

00:32:20.280 --> 00:32:24.760
[Guest]: Nandita Krishna has written this wonderful book on sacred trees and sacred groves.

00:32:24.760 --> 00:32:31.600
[Guest]: You know, we are original tree huggers, we are the original rock worshippers and river

00:32:31.600 --> 00:32:32.600
[Guest]: worshippers.

00:32:32.600 --> 00:32:39.920
[Guest]: And that connects us not just to our own Vedic past, but to past in Egypt, where, you know,

00:32:39.920 --> 00:32:42.200
[Guest]: the pyramids were built.

00:32:42.200 --> 00:32:47.200
[Guest]: My father passed away recently and the death ceremonies that surround an Indian death are

00:32:47.200 --> 00:32:50.800
[Guest]: very similar to sending off a pharaoh to the next life.

00:32:50.800 --> 00:32:58.920
[Guest]: So we sent my father off with a cow image, with an umbrella, with slippers, with clothes,

00:32:58.920 --> 00:33:00.680
[Guest]: with his favorite food.

00:33:00.680 --> 00:33:02.680
[Guest]: I think that's so wonderful.

00:33:02.680 --> 00:33:09.020
[Guest]: The rituals that I disdained as a child are so meaningful to me now that we are living

00:33:09.020 --> 00:33:14.040
[Guest]: more and more in a world where we are, our life is shorn of meaning.

00:33:14.040 --> 00:33:20.480
[Guest]: Life has been the vestiges of the rituals that connected us to milestones.

00:33:20.480 --> 00:33:27.080
[Guest]: You know, African cultures, when a man reached a certain age would send them off to the hunt

00:33:27.080 --> 00:33:29.800
[Guest]: and they would have these markings and tattoos on it.

00:33:29.800 --> 00:33:33.560
[Guest]: We still have that, but we have forgotten them.

00:33:33.560 --> 00:33:40.680
[Guest]: So if you admit faith as essential to your well-being, as I have come to believe, then

00:33:40.680 --> 00:33:42.360
[Guest]: you have to choose your faith.

00:33:42.360 --> 00:33:44.140
[Guest]: And as an adult, you can.

00:33:44.140 --> 00:33:47.480
[Guest]: And I chose the faith that I was born into.

00:33:47.480 --> 00:33:50.200
[Guest]: I haven't found enough to give it up.

00:33:50.200 --> 00:33:54.280
[Guest]: And I like the fact that there are women goddesses, there aren't too many faiths in which there

00:33:54.280 --> 00:33:55.280
[Guest]: are women goddesses.

00:33:55.280 --> 00:33:59.240
[Guest]: I think that was a key element, which makes me like Hinduism.

00:33:59.240 --> 00:34:04.560
[Guest]: And I specifically like the Hinduism of the left-handed path, as my mother would call

00:34:04.560 --> 00:34:08.880
[Guest]: it, which is there in Bengal, which is there in Kerala, which is there in Nepal, when I

00:34:08.880 --> 00:34:09.880
[Guest]: went to see the goddess.

00:34:09.880 --> 00:34:14.760
[Guest]: The left-handed goddess tantric, it embraces what Carl Jung calls the shadow, which is

00:34:14.760 --> 00:34:19.840
[Guest]: the quote-unquote, the so-called bad parts of yourself, the things that you suppress.

00:34:19.840 --> 00:34:28.320
[Guest]: It embraces sacrifice, animal sacrifice, it embraces blood, wine, madhu, the goddess drinks

00:34:28.320 --> 00:34:29.640
[Guest]: blood and wine.

00:34:29.640 --> 00:34:36.080
[Guest]: It embraces all the things that have been sanitized out of, you know, the, how should

00:34:36.080 --> 00:34:38.280
[Guest]: we call it, the middle path Hinduism.

00:34:38.280 --> 00:34:40.600
[Guest]: So I like the left-handed path.

00:34:40.600 --> 00:34:45.840
[Guest]: I like Chinnamasta, the tantric goddess who cut off her head and dances on corpses.

00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:50.480
[Guest]: So the reason to embrace faith is intellectual for me.

00:34:50.480 --> 00:34:56.280
[Guest]: The reason to embrace Hinduism is the marvelous variety and the fact that I am interested

00:34:56.280 --> 00:35:03.440
[Guest]: in Carl Jung and dreams and transcendence and how to end the whole, you know, marijuana,

00:35:03.440 --> 00:35:07.880
[Guest]: if you have to say it, and effects of it thereof.

00:35:07.880 --> 00:35:10.560
[Guest]: And the fact that people in Bangalore are missing.

00:35:10.560 --> 00:35:15.760
[Guest]: One of the most interesting things that I've attended recently is a firewalking ceremony.

00:35:15.760 --> 00:35:19.040
[Guest]: And if you like, we can talk about that.

00:35:19.040 --> 00:35:21.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, we'll come back to it.

00:35:21.040 --> 00:35:25.200
[Amit Varma]: There's so much to unpack here and this is what kind of fascinates me about everything

00:35:25.200 --> 00:35:30.600
[Amit Varma]: that you've just said and which you've written about in your book is this notion of faith

00:35:30.600 --> 00:35:34.880
[Amit Varma]: of the instrumental qualities of faith, where you point out that, you know, like you point

00:35:34.880 --> 00:35:39.840
[Amit Varma]: to the Time magazine article that it can help us lead more fulfilled lives and we are happier

00:35:39.840 --> 00:35:45.240
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth, thereby pointing out how, you know, faith is useful.

00:35:45.240 --> 00:35:47.200
[Amit Varma]: I mean, faith is important because it is useful.

00:35:47.200 --> 00:35:50.600
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't matter if it's true or not, as long as it's useful.

00:35:50.600 --> 00:35:54.280
[Amit Varma]: And this brings me to a very interesting thought because I often get semantic about, you know,

00:35:54.280 --> 00:35:58.480
[Amit Varma]: atheism and agnostic people think of them as separate points on a continuum.

00:35:58.480 --> 00:36:02.680
[Amit Varma]: But you can actually be atheist and agnostic at the same time because atheism has to do

00:36:02.680 --> 00:36:07.280
[Amit Varma]: with belief and an atheist is someone who has an absence of belief.

00:36:07.280 --> 00:36:09.080
[Amit Varma]: He doesn't believe that there's no God.

00:36:09.080 --> 00:36:12.880
[Amit Varma]: There's simply an absence of belief, you know, much as, you know, not collecting stamps is

00:36:12.880 --> 00:36:13.880
[Amit Varma]: not a hobby.

00:36:13.880 --> 00:36:15.920
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, it's not a belief itself.

00:36:15.920 --> 00:36:16.920
[Amit Varma]: It's an absence.

00:36:16.920 --> 00:36:20.640
[Amit Varma]: And while atheism deals with belief, agnosticism deals with knowledge.

00:36:20.640 --> 00:36:26.040
[Amit Varma]: And what it means is an agnostic holds a position that you cannot know whether there is a God

00:36:26.040 --> 00:36:27.040
[Amit Varma]: or not.

00:36:27.040 --> 00:36:28.120
[Amit Varma]: There is epistemic humility.

00:36:28.120 --> 00:36:31.840
[Amit Varma]: So it is possible to be both an atheist and an agnostic if you look at it technically

00:36:31.840 --> 00:36:37.000
[Amit Varma]: because you can both not believe and at the same time accept that there are some things

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:38.280
[Amit Varma]: you cannot know.

00:36:38.280 --> 00:36:42.400
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting addition to that is that besides being an atheist and an agnostic,

00:36:42.400 --> 00:36:48.080
[Amit Varma]: you can now be a person of faith also because without believing and accepting that you cannot

00:36:48.080 --> 00:36:53.760
[Amit Varma]: know, you can still embrace faith because of the utility it has in your life.

00:36:53.760 --> 00:36:57.920
[Amit Varma]: And you know, that sense that you're part of a community, the comfort that you get from

00:36:57.920 --> 00:37:03.560
[Amit Varma]: these rituals and traditions, I mean, in fact, it again, just thinking aloud, it reminds

00:37:03.560 --> 00:37:08.520
[Amit Varma]: me of a book by Steven Landsberg called The Big Questions, in which he says that most

00:37:08.520 --> 00:37:11.680
[Amit Varma]: people who profess to believe in God actually don't believe in God.

00:37:11.680 --> 00:37:15.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, they say they believe, but if it comes to the crunch, you know, so again, I

00:37:15.640 --> 00:37:19.720
[Amit Varma]: mean, it seems to be coming from the way of thinking that, hey, religion is useful even

00:37:19.720 --> 00:37:21.480
[Amit Varma]: if it isn't true.

00:37:21.480 --> 00:37:26.160
[Amit Varma]: So what's your sense of, you know, you've been to all these places, you mingled with

00:37:26.160 --> 00:37:32.000
[Amit Varma]: all these religious people in the sense of this kind of balance between usefulness and

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:33.200
[Amit Varma]: belief.

00:37:33.200 --> 00:37:34.800
[Guest]: What are your observations?

00:37:34.800 --> 00:37:40.280
[Guest]: So I both agree and disagree with Karl Marx's statement about religion being the opiate

00:37:40.280 --> 00:37:43.240
[Guest]: of the masses or the opium of the masses.

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:44.240
[Guest]: He was right.

00:37:44.240 --> 00:37:51.160
[Guest]: It is actually, it has the benefit that of comfort and other worldliness that a drug

00:37:51.160 --> 00:37:52.160
[Guest]: gives.

00:37:52.160 --> 00:37:58.920
[Guest]: But what touched me was the way a devotee, the truly faithful, deals with God has nothing

00:37:58.920 --> 00:37:59.920
[Guest]: to do with mass.

00:37:59.920 --> 00:38:01.440
[Guest]: It's a very particular thing.

00:38:01.440 --> 00:38:07.040
[Guest]: You know, I saw women in Palani doing Anga Pradashnam, where you roll around the temple

00:38:07.040 --> 00:38:12.600
[Guest]: and saying Muruga, Muruga, and it was her, from her face, from her demeanor, from the

00:38:12.600 --> 00:38:18.520
[Guest]: supplicancy with which she rolled, and from the eyes, which were tuned in with God, she

00:38:18.520 --> 00:38:20.920
[Guest]: was not paying attention to the surroundings.

00:38:20.920 --> 00:38:26.600
[Guest]: You could tell the fervor with which she believed that if she did this particular thing, that

00:38:26.600 --> 00:38:31.680
[Guest]: her problem, whatever that specific problem was, whether it was son or a daughter being

00:38:31.680 --> 00:38:33.240
[Guest]: sick would be solved.

00:38:33.240 --> 00:38:39.720
[Guest]: So it is a connection, this sort of connection, I envy, you know, and I saw this countless

00:38:39.720 --> 00:38:40.720
[Guest]: times.

00:38:40.720 --> 00:38:46.400
[Guest]: I mean, mostly in South Indian temples, because I could tune in very quickly to the nuances

00:38:46.400 --> 00:38:47.400
[Guest]: of it.

00:38:47.400 --> 00:38:52.280
[Guest]: So you go to Ambalapura, the palpaisam was made for the God, and the priest would go

00:38:52.280 --> 00:38:58.000
[Guest]: out every day and call out Vasudeva, Vasudeva three times.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:02.160
[Guest]: And you're calling as if you're calling your son who is playing in the cricket field, and

00:39:02.160 --> 00:39:05.080
[Guest]: I know you're writing a book on cricket to come back.

00:39:05.080 --> 00:39:13.240
[Guest]: So it is a, it is a feat of imagination, and the word that is used by my mother is bhavna,

00:39:13.240 --> 00:39:15.120
[Guest]: bhavana in Tamil.

00:39:15.120 --> 00:39:21.000
[Guest]: So okay, so assume you're a skeptic like I am, why not cultivate faith just to improve

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:23.360
[Guest]: your imagination is the question I have.

00:39:23.360 --> 00:39:28.520
[Guest]: I mean, I think there are many ways to do it, the art of drawing, there are books about

00:39:28.520 --> 00:39:34.720
[Guest]: it, how to, and there are lots of people in the West who've made a fortune by teaching

00:39:34.720 --> 00:39:40.040
[Guest]: you how to cultivate your creativity, but rituals are a great way where you can look

00:39:40.040 --> 00:39:45.840
[Guest]: at a grain of rice and see a universe, you look at a stone and see the Shiva, the destroyer

00:39:45.840 --> 00:39:50.720
[Guest]: of the universe, you hold the Nataraja pose in your Bharatanatyam, and then you become

00:39:50.720 --> 00:39:55.320
[Guest]: that goddess as so many Bharatanatyam dances in Chennai demonstrate.

00:39:55.320 --> 00:40:00.840
[Guest]: And the best Kathak, as my friend Madhu Nataraj in Bangalore tells me, some of the finest

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:06.200
[Guest]: Kathak choreographies or the creations were done by a Muslim Nawab, who pretended he was

00:40:06.200 --> 00:40:08.160
[Guest]: Krishna and or Radha.

00:40:08.160 --> 00:40:13.840
[Guest]: So these are feats, flights of fancy that will help you no matter what area of life

00:40:13.840 --> 00:40:16.120
[Guest]: that you would like to be part of.

00:40:16.120 --> 00:40:21.920
[Guest]: So there are two things I find that religion is about, you take it all down, so one is

00:40:21.920 --> 00:40:27.480
[Guest]: bhavna or imagination, the other is sharanagati or self-surrender, self-surrender has to do

00:40:27.480 --> 00:40:33.280
[Guest]: with, it's not about giving up on free will, it is about applying for a job at Apple or

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:39.000
[Guest]: Microsoft doing the best you can, and then you know having this faith which Ramanujan

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:45.320
[Guest]: the mathematical genius had is that something is beyond my spectrum that will help me, and

00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:51.360
[Guest]: devotees have that, and usually they are down and out, usually somebody is sick, it is visiting

00:40:51.360 --> 00:40:58.200
[Guest]: a temple is, if you see, if you go beyond the praying and everything, it is about being

00:40:58.200 --> 00:41:04.320
[Guest]: caught in a quagmire of hopes and dreams, you stand in the temple, in any temple and

00:41:04.320 --> 00:41:10.760
[Guest]: you're surrounded by murmuring people, and it's as if you are in a cloud of dream, fear

00:41:10.760 --> 00:41:15.920
[Guest]: and hope, and they've all come to this one place to solve it, to solve their problems,

00:41:15.920 --> 00:41:21.640
[Guest]: and if you are a feeling person like me, you will feel that, and then that's the transition

00:41:21.640 --> 00:41:27.200
[Guest]: from cerebral to visceral, when and I truly believe what Diana said in all her books about

00:41:27.200 --> 00:41:35.320
[Guest]: the sea of the yatra, yatra is a crossing, and the more you go, more you subjugate yourself,

00:41:35.320 --> 00:41:42.280
[Guest]: the more you get rid of this ego mind, and get into the feeling mind, you will be touched,

00:41:42.280 --> 00:41:46.360
[Guest]: and as I was, and it is a privilege to be touched in that way.

00:41:46.360 --> 00:41:51.080
[Amit Varma]: And I'm very sort of intrigued by the role of both rituals and food in that, I mean food

00:41:51.080 --> 00:41:55.920
[Amit Varma]: of course is a part of some rituals also, but you know, deep associations with each

00:41:55.920 --> 00:42:00.560
[Amit Varma]: of these places, and we'll kind of talk about some of them, but what it kind of again strikes

00:42:00.560 --> 00:42:04.520
[Amit Varma]: me is that, you know, again when I teach my writing course to go back to that, I'll often

00:42:04.520 --> 00:42:10.180
[Amit Varma]: tell the people who participate that if you want to, you know, one useful hack in terms

00:42:10.180 --> 00:42:12.920
[Amit Varma]: of building a routine is build a ritual around your writing.

00:42:12.920 --> 00:42:17.440
[Amit Varma]: So you know, in the sense that you get up at the same time, you make a cup of coffee,

00:42:17.440 --> 00:42:20.960
[Amit Varma]: you sit at the same place, you listen to the same playlist, and you're more likely to get

00:42:20.960 --> 00:42:22.480
[Amit Varma]: into the writing groove.

00:42:22.480 --> 00:42:26.800
[Amit Varma]: And the reason for that is actually a scientific one, you know, neurologists would say neurons

00:42:26.800 --> 00:42:29.100
[Amit Varma]: that fire together wire together.

00:42:29.100 --> 00:42:32.200
[Amit Varma]: So when these things kind of come together, they can work together.

00:42:32.200 --> 00:42:36.160
[Amit Varma]: And it seems that there is a deep truth there, which religion hit upon, because you have

00:42:36.160 --> 00:42:39.760
[Amit Varma]: all of these things coming together, you have ritual coming together, you have food coming

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:44.720
[Amit Varma]: together, you have, you know, certain ways of doing things, different customs in different

00:42:44.720 --> 00:42:50.240
[Amit Varma]: places like the Sufis in Ajmer may, you know, whirl and do all of those things, you have

00:42:50.240 --> 00:42:53.000
[Amit Varma]: these separate, distinct rituals.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:57.800
[Amit Varma]: And it therefore strikes me that it doesn't really matter whether there is a God or not,

00:42:57.800 --> 00:43:01.280
[Amit Varma]: or whether you know what the religion holds out as facts are true or not.

00:43:01.280 --> 00:43:05.640
[Amit Varma]: What is true is that all of these, they can come together and they can kind of put you

00:43:05.640 --> 00:43:10.040
[Amit Varma]: in a particular state of mind, which can, as you so eloquently put it, make the whole

00:43:10.040 --> 00:43:11.040
[Amit Varma]: experience visceral.

00:43:11.040 --> 00:43:15.600
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I was going to ask you earlier when you were talking about how food can be affected

00:43:15.600 --> 00:43:18.600
[Amit Varma]: by how it's presented and everything around it.

00:43:18.600 --> 00:43:22.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, you've mentioned at one point in your book that if you were asked, you know,

00:43:22.120 --> 00:43:26.200
[Amit Varma]: if you had one meal to have before you left the planet, what would you have?

00:43:26.200 --> 00:43:31.240
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned breakfast in Haridwar, especially their samosas.

00:43:31.240 --> 00:43:36.640
[Amit Varma]: Do you think part of the reason that food tasted so good to you is everything that was

00:43:36.640 --> 00:43:38.280
[Amit Varma]: around it as well?

00:43:38.280 --> 00:43:43.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, so are all these things also part of religion, that religion is not just about

00:43:43.880 --> 00:43:49.120
[Amit Varma]: the bland fact of there being a God and everything associated with that, but all of these local

00:43:49.120 --> 00:43:50.920
[Amit Varma]: things also play a part in that?

00:43:50.920 --> 00:43:52.160
[Guest]: 100% Amit.

00:43:52.160 --> 00:43:58.720
[Guest]: I think that this is why they say when we offer it to the God, we call it Naivedyam

00:43:58.720 --> 00:44:02.760
[Guest]: and it becomes Prasadam or Prasad after the God has blessed it.

00:44:02.760 --> 00:44:08.120
[Guest]: And 100% I believe the taste of the food, the divinity associated with it, the feeling

00:44:08.120 --> 00:44:14.160
[Guest]: that what you are having is the God's blessing contributes to your well-being.

00:44:14.160 --> 00:44:20.200
[Guest]: So I actually, after these trips of mine, I'm a little, I have started looking at this

00:44:20.200 --> 00:44:25.080
[Guest]: notion of the energy around the food, energy around the cook a little bit more carefully,

00:44:25.080 --> 00:44:29.480
[Guest]: haven't come to a conclusion yet, but I actually think there is something to the fact what

00:44:29.480 --> 00:44:34.280
[Guest]: we Hindus have discovered in India and what the faithful have discovered in every state

00:44:34.280 --> 00:44:41.440
[Guest]: is that the milieu surrounding the food and its preparation matter and it makes a difference.

00:44:41.440 --> 00:44:47.080
[Guest]: And it is a subtle difference, perhaps we have lost the art of recognizing it, but I

00:44:47.080 --> 00:44:52.440
[Guest]: have come to believe there is a difference and I am trying in small ways to figure out

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:55.640
[Guest]: experiments to figure out that difference.

00:44:55.640 --> 00:45:01.080
[Guest]: But I wanted to add, I'm sure if you haven't done this already for your students, the Paris

00:45:01.080 --> 00:45:05.800
[Guest]: Review interviews, which are available online for free, I'm sure you know them, but they

00:45:05.800 --> 00:45:11.560
[Guest]: are great examples of the routines and superstitions that writers develop.

00:45:11.560 --> 00:45:17.000
[Guest]: And one that stuck to my mind was of Ernest Hemingway, of course, is the great one who

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:21.640
[Guest]: wrote and when the writing was good, he would stop and then go out drinking and come back

00:45:21.640 --> 00:45:22.640
[Guest]: the next day and work.

00:45:22.640 --> 00:45:27.880
[Guest]: But the other one was, I think Dan Brown got these shoes that were anti-gravity shoes and

00:45:27.880 --> 00:45:33.480
[Guest]: would sort of hang on the ceiling upside down as a writing ritual routine.

00:45:33.480 --> 00:45:36.440
[Guest]: But that was for your students.

00:45:36.440 --> 00:45:39.720
[Guest]: And yeah, and I think I've answered your other question about that.

00:45:39.720 --> 00:45:40.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I know.

00:45:40.720 --> 00:45:41.720
[Amit Varma]: That's fantastic.

00:45:41.720 --> 00:45:45.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I do cite the Writers at Work series, as you know, the Paris Review interviews were

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:48.720
[Amit Varma]: called to my students, I talk about the Hemingway interview also, because he said some really

00:45:48.720 --> 00:45:53.640
[Amit Varma]: interesting things in that I haven't read the Dan Brown interview, but I now will.

00:45:53.640 --> 00:45:57.080
[Amit Varma]: And this is probably a good time then to, you know, before we get down to the book,

00:45:57.080 --> 00:46:02.160
[Amit Varma]: to talk about the craft of writing, like you are someone who's been a prolific columnist,

00:46:02.160 --> 00:46:06.160
[Amit Varma]: you've kind of written all these years, you've also written a bunch of books.

00:46:06.160 --> 00:46:08.520
[Amit Varma]: So what is kind of the process like?

00:46:08.520 --> 00:46:10.640
[Amit Varma]: What is the column process like?

00:46:10.640 --> 00:46:11.840
[Amit Varma]: Do you face writer's block?

00:46:11.840 --> 00:46:14.440
[Amit Varma]: Do you have hacks to deal with it?

00:46:14.440 --> 00:46:19.520
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, how has you know, looking back over the years, how has sort of your craft

00:46:19.520 --> 00:46:21.520
[Amit Varma]: evolved and the way you approach?

00:46:21.520 --> 00:46:25.360
[Amit Varma]: I mean, let's talk about columns first, you know, can you can you give me some insight

00:46:25.360 --> 00:46:26.360
[Amit Varma]: on that?

00:46:26.360 --> 00:46:27.360
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:46:27.360 --> 00:46:30.600
[Guest]: So I'll go from the details to the broader one.

00:46:30.600 --> 00:46:33.960
[Guest]: I actually believe in Hemingway's words, kill your darlings.

00:46:33.960 --> 00:46:40.160
[Guest]: So then if you write a paragraph that you're very proud of, you need to look at it again.

00:46:40.160 --> 00:46:44.420
[Guest]: And you need to kill your darling, by which he meant that when you fall in love with your

00:46:44.420 --> 00:46:47.920
[Guest]: own writing, examine it with a little bit more critical eyes.

00:46:47.920 --> 00:46:53.280
[Guest]: I also small things like don't use the same word in the same paragraph or within two or

00:46:53.280 --> 00:46:54.280
[Guest]: three sentences.

00:46:54.280 --> 00:46:59.760
[Guest]: The thesaurus should be your best friend, because you it will actually force you to

00:46:59.760 --> 00:47:00.760
[Guest]: look at.

00:47:00.760 --> 00:47:04.120
[Guest]: So if you're struggling for a word, look at it in thesaurus, it would it may enlighten

00:47:04.120 --> 00:47:06.240
[Guest]: you on how to actually present it.

00:47:06.240 --> 00:47:11.520
[Guest]: The beginning and the end are the most important aspects of a column, especially the end because

00:47:11.520 --> 00:47:16.760
[Guest]: ideally, in this age of soundbite, think about coming up with a soundbite or one line soundbite

00:47:16.760 --> 00:47:21.400
[Guest]: which encapsulates your column, that will be probably the most important sentence, right?

00:47:21.400 --> 00:47:25.240
[Guest]: Like a poker player, don't reveal your hand all at once.

00:47:25.240 --> 00:47:28.840
[Guest]: So a New York Times editor once told me that in the first paragraph, you're pretty much

00:47:28.840 --> 00:47:31.960
[Guest]: written the whole essay, don't reveal your hand so much.

00:47:31.960 --> 00:47:36.000
[Guest]: So do it gradually to do a little bit of zigzag to maintain the tension.

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:40.160
[Guest]: These are the things that all of us learn once you do it enough.

00:47:40.160 --> 00:47:46.000
[Guest]: As far as my column, Raju Narasetty, who is known to both of us, described my column.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:52.720
[Guest]: He was my first editor and he said it is being using the small everyday act to come up with

00:47:52.720 --> 00:47:53.720
[Guest]: a big picture.

00:47:53.720 --> 00:47:58.400
[Guest]: So that has been sort of how I approach column writing where you use simple things to come

00:47:58.400 --> 00:48:03.080
[Guest]: up with a bigger philosophical, whether it's philosophical or a larger picture.

00:48:03.080 --> 00:48:07.140
[Guest]: And that's how that's how I think and that's how I look view the column.

00:48:07.140 --> 00:48:08.560
[Guest]: What do I do for that?

00:48:08.560 --> 00:48:10.720
[Guest]: So there are many kinds of columnists.

00:48:10.720 --> 00:48:14.760
[Guest]: You are one who links events to philosophy.

00:48:14.760 --> 00:48:21.200
[Guest]: I am not an event to philosophy person, partially because I'm not a politics junkie like so

00:48:21.200 --> 00:48:23.560
[Guest]: many columnists are in this country.

00:48:23.560 --> 00:48:29.320
[Guest]: I am much more of a everyday thing, small things, linking it to bigger truth.

00:48:29.320 --> 00:48:33.020
[Guest]: So that in that itself, there are two types of columnists.

00:48:33.020 --> 00:48:37.080
[Guest]: If you would like to be Amit Verma type of columnist, I have no words for you.

00:48:37.080 --> 00:48:43.480
[Guest]: If you would like to be a sort of a humorous, a little bit playful, again, what I said about

00:48:43.480 --> 00:48:49.400
[Guest]: seeing the universe in a grain of sand type of columnist, I would say, first of all, when

00:48:49.400 --> 00:48:54.880
[Guest]: you stand in a line, don't look at your smartphone, talk to people around you, whether when you're

00:48:54.880 --> 00:49:02.360
[Guest]: going to buy fruit, try your best not to use after COVID, stop ordering on Amazon, actually

00:49:02.360 --> 00:49:08.400
[Guest]: go out to your Monday and find people, because in order to write about life, as I do, you

00:49:08.400 --> 00:49:10.080
[Guest]: have to engage with life.

00:49:10.080 --> 00:49:14.040
[Guest]: And more and more these days, it's become very easy to sit at home and look at the computer

00:49:14.040 --> 00:49:15.160
[Guest]: all day.

00:49:15.160 --> 00:49:19.760
[Guest]: And the problem with that is that you won't get flashes of insight, which only come when

00:49:19.760 --> 00:49:22.720
[Guest]: you're bored, when your mind is idle.

00:49:22.720 --> 00:49:27.320
[Guest]: And you have to force yourself to give yourself that moment of idleness when you're not checking

00:49:27.320 --> 00:49:28.320
[Guest]: your smartphone.

00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:33.600
[Guest]: So I don't, I, for example, some, a few things I have done, I removed Facebook, Twitter,

00:49:33.600 --> 00:49:39.920
[Guest]: all from my phone, I go through last phases of the month, when I disengage email, which

00:49:39.920 --> 00:49:44.560
[Guest]: is easy to do if you have a smartphone, I mute WhatsApp messages.

00:49:44.560 --> 00:49:47.880
[Guest]: So notifications, muting is a very important thing.

00:49:47.880 --> 00:49:48.880
[Guest]: I love my phone.

00:49:48.880 --> 00:49:53.960
[Guest]: So if you're addicted to checking your phone, as I am, at least mute the notifications,

00:49:53.960 --> 00:49:57.480
[Guest]: whenever possible, forget your phone at home when you go out.

00:49:57.480 --> 00:50:01.400
[Guest]: So these are ways in which you engage with the present when you engage with people, talking

00:50:01.400 --> 00:50:03.960
[Guest]: to people is a good one.

00:50:03.960 --> 00:50:08.560
[Guest]: Try to compartmentalize your life, so that you're writing time, do the Pomodoro, I use

00:50:08.560 --> 00:50:13.360
[Guest]: the Pomodoro technique, which is 20 minutes without surfing the internet and stuff like

00:50:13.360 --> 00:50:14.360
[Guest]: that.

00:50:14.360 --> 00:50:18.840
[Guest]: I used to have an app called Freedom, which is installed, where you basically shuts off

00:50:18.840 --> 00:50:22.440
[Guest]: your computer and you can't open Chrome and nothing will happen.

00:50:22.440 --> 00:50:24.880
[Guest]: So I have been known to do that.

00:50:24.880 --> 00:50:29.280
[Guest]: Essentially the way I write a column and I did a weekly column for Mint was that be on

00:50:29.280 --> 00:50:35.120
[Guest]: the lookout for an idea that is somewhat topical, because nobody cares about so essentially,

00:50:35.120 --> 00:50:40.320
[Guest]: have attention for festivals that come up, have some notion of what's going on in the

00:50:40.320 --> 00:50:41.320
[Guest]: world.

00:50:41.320 --> 00:50:43.840
[Guest]: And tangentially be on the lookout for that idea.

00:50:43.840 --> 00:50:49.720
[Guest]: And usually the idea would percolate, I would make notes longhand on A4 paper.

00:50:49.720 --> 00:50:53.120
[Guest]: And because you're on deadline, I would sit down to write the column and pretty much finish

00:50:53.120 --> 00:50:58.800
[Guest]: it in the span of a day, 800 words is easy to do in a span of a day, if you have enough

00:50:58.800 --> 00:50:59.800
[Guest]: notes.

00:50:59.800 --> 00:51:05.040
[Guest]: Sometimes there were times when there would be writer's block, but one study actually

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:06.040
[Guest]: helped me.

00:51:06.040 --> 00:51:12.680
[Guest]: Study was examining the words of people who were forced to write and the words of people

00:51:12.680 --> 00:51:15.200
[Guest]: who wrote when the muse was sitting on their shoulder.

00:51:15.200 --> 00:51:19.720
[Guest]: So basically it got the control group of say 50 people and said, okay, right.

00:51:19.720 --> 00:51:23.880
[Guest]: And then control the experimental group of 50 people who were told, okay, write when

00:51:23.880 --> 00:51:25.720
[Guest]: you have the urge to write.

00:51:25.720 --> 00:51:27.400
[Guest]: And the output was, there was no difference.

00:51:27.400 --> 00:51:32.960
[Guest]: So I said, you know, I don't feel like writing, this is bad writing, all the negative narratives

00:51:32.960 --> 00:51:34.520
[Guest]: that come into your head.

00:51:34.520 --> 00:51:37.800
[Guest]: You just, I used to think of that study and said, you know what?

00:51:37.800 --> 00:51:42.960
[Guest]: I may think this is stupid and bad, but the output when people look at it, guess what?

00:51:42.960 --> 00:51:44.480
[Guest]: The study said there'll be no difference.

00:51:44.480 --> 00:51:47.120
[Guest]: So that's how I forced myself to write.

00:51:47.120 --> 00:51:52.900
[Guest]: So I think attention is the most important thing a writer has.

00:51:52.900 --> 00:51:58.400
[Guest]: What you train your attention to focus on is priceless for a writer.

00:51:58.400 --> 00:52:03.080
[Guest]: And to make it count, you know, focus attention on things that matter.

00:52:03.080 --> 00:52:06.600
[Guest]: I mean, go to kacheris or go to concerts because guess what?

00:52:06.600 --> 00:52:09.640
[Guest]: There are a few places when insight will strike.

00:52:09.640 --> 00:52:10.640
[Guest]: Everybody says shower.

00:52:10.640 --> 00:52:15.160
[Guest]: I get insight when I listen to Hindustani music or Carnatic music.

00:52:15.160 --> 00:52:21.480
[Guest]: And I think the sitting back and letting your mind wander is a very special thing.

00:52:21.480 --> 00:52:23.800
[Guest]: And you have to figure out ways to do that.

00:52:23.800 --> 00:52:27.800
[Guest]: Whether you end up being a birdwatcher like me and standing in the balcony and looking

00:52:27.800 --> 00:52:34.760
[Guest]: out or you're a runner, running, I mean, runners are a great way to figure out a way for you

00:52:34.760 --> 00:52:35.960
[Amit Varma]: to be bored.

00:52:35.960 --> 00:52:40.800
[Amit Varma]: This is all fantastic and very wise advice, you know, especially that bit about how, you

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:43.720
[Amit Varma]: know, if you're forced to write a lot, that will actually help you.

00:52:43.720 --> 00:52:47.800
[Amit Varma]: Because the one thing that I keep saying is that what leads to excellence, iterations

00:52:47.800 --> 00:52:48.800
[Amit Varma]: lead to excellence.

00:52:48.800 --> 00:52:51.800
[Amit Varma]: You keep doing something again and again and again and again.

00:52:51.800 --> 00:52:55.600
[Amit Varma]: And that's much more likely to happen if you force yourself to do it, rather than if you

00:52:55.600 --> 00:52:59.640
[Amit Varma]: just sit around and wait for the muse to strike you, as you said.

00:52:59.640 --> 00:53:04.400
[Amit Varma]: And you know, since you sort of now created this framework of Amit Verma kind of columnist

